<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="128" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1485,1908]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1557,1583]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The calling song of the species does not consist of a homogenous sequence of echemes as in all other known species of the group, but the very short echemes are grouped in small series of three echemes separated from the next series by a larger interval (
<figureCitation box="[545,613,1629,1655]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1988,2012]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,672,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-293@16.[151,1436,669,1965]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 8. Oscillograms of the calling songs of species of the Mecopoda confracta subgroup. Overview (12 s sections)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141299" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141299/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[626,642,1629,1655]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1241,1265]" captionTargetBox="[192,1398,188,1201]" captionTargetId="figure-19@17.[180,1407,181,1216]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 9. Oscillograms of the calling songs of species of the Mecopoda confracta subgroup. Details (1 s sections). In M. sismondoi sp. nov. synchronous registration of movement of left tegmen and sound (upper line: upward deflection indicating opening, downward closing; lower line: sound)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141303/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="128" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1485,1908]" box="[199,1408,1665,1692]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1665,1691]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Description.</emphasis>
Morphologically no difference to other species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[954,1099,1665,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confracta">
<emphasis box="[954,1099,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">M. confracta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup (
<bibRefCitation author="Liu, C. - X. &amp; Heller, K. - G. &amp; Wang, X. - S. &amp; Yang, Z. &amp; Wu, C. &amp; Liu, F. &amp; Zhang, T." box="[1225,1397,1665,1691]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128" pagination="296 - 310" refId="ref25603" refString="Liu, C. - X., Heller, K. - G., Wang, X. - S., Yang, Z., Wu, C., Liu, F. &amp; Zhang, T. (2020) Taxonomy of a katydid genus Mecopoda Serville (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae, Mecopodinae) from East Asia. Zootaxa, 4758 (2), 296 - 310. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4758.2.5" type="journal article" year="2020">
Liu 
<emphasis box="[1273,1329,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1485,1908]" box="[199,1397,1701,1728]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,1701,1727]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Measurements</emphasis>
(in mm): pronotum length 8; tegmen length 56; tegmen width 13.5; hind femora length 43.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1485,1908]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,379,1737,1763]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Chromosomes:</emphasis>
2n = 29, FN = 52; pairs 1, 4 and 6–14 metacentric, 2, 3 and 5 acrocentric, X chromosome metacentric (
<figureCitation box="[297,380,1773,1800]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1235,1259]" captionTargetBox="[261,1329,186,1204]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[249,1338,181,1210]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 15. C-banded karyotypes (left side) and mitotic metaphase (right side) of five Mecopoda species with different chromosome number (2n). Karyotypes are reconstructed by arranging homologous chromosomes in order of decreasing size. X, sex chromosome." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141316" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141316/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="128" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,1485,1908]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,420,1809,1835]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Derivatio nominis.</emphasis>
Name remembering to the Indian monk Mahinda who arrived in Mihintale, the 
<typeStatus box="[1317,1365,1810,1836]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">type</typeStatus>
locality, according to religious myths traveling through the air, founding Buddhism in 
<collectingCountry box="[1071,1185,1845,1871]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
. The insect was found on the stupa which was built to celebrate this event. Substantive in genitive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
